{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Use Australian English|date=May 2013}} {{Infobox organization |name = The Fremantle Society, Inc. |bgcolor = #00719a |fgcolor = white |image = |size = 100 |alt = Stylised 'FS' logo of the Society. |caption = |map = <!-- optional --> |msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px --> |malt = <!-- map alt text --> |mcaption = <!-- optional --> |abbreviation = |motto = For Fremantle people and places |formation = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1972|1|1}} |type = <!-- GO, NGO, IGO, INGO, etc --> |status = Association (ASIC registration number: <!--Previously: WA A0750162N-->136085946)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://connectonline.asic.gov.au/RegistrySearch/faces/landing/panelSearch.jspx?searchType=OrgAndBusNm&searchText=A0750162N&searchTab=search&_adf.ctrl-state=ourgmm3qw_34 |title=Search ASIC Registers |accessdate=28 May 2014 |author=[[Australian Securities and Investments Commission]] }}</ref> |purpose = Heritage |headquarters = Victoria Hall 179 High St, Fremantle WA 6160 |location = |coords = {{Coord|-32.055|115.741}} |region_served = [[Fremantle, Western Australia]] |membership = |language = English |leader_title = President |leader_name = John Dowson |main_organ = Committee |parent_organization = <!-- if one --> |affiliations = <!-- if any --> |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = {{URL|fremantlesociety.org.au}} |remarks = }}'''The Fremantle Society''' is a community-based culture and heritage advocacy group in [[Fremantle, Western Australia]]. It was formed in 1972 to prevent demolition of historic buildings in Fremantle and to assist in their development.<ref name="FfF">{{cite book |last1=Davidson |first1=Ron |first2=Dianne |last2=Davidson |title=Fighting for Fremantle: a history of The Fremantle Society |publisher=[[Fremantle Press]] |year=2010 }}</ref> As the significance of Fremantle's built heritage came to be more widely recognised and respected (by the [[City of Fremantle|City]], and property owners), the focus of the Fremantle Society has evolved to include more of the [[cultural heritage]] of the area.
Various projects over time have highlighted Fremantle heritage,<ref>{{Citation | author1=Gore, Stuart | author2=Reece, Rob | title=[Interview with Stuart Gore] | publication-date=1982 | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/159331779 | accessdate=14 May 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Fremantle Society | author2=Interiors Project, 1992 | title=Interiors Project, 1992. Drawing record -- A3 collection : a photographic archive of Fremantle West End interiors | publication-date=1995 | publisher=The Society | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/21778411 | accessdate=14 May 2013 }}</ref> as well as advocating consideration of heritage in planning schemes.<ref>{{Citation | author1=The Fremantle Society Inc | title=The future Fremantle : a discussion document by the Fremantle Society on planning, for the future of Fremantle | publication-date=1978 | publisher=The Fremantle Society Inc | edition=1st | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/173182755 | accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref>
When the City's precinct system was established in the 1990s to provide interaction between the City and groups of residents, the Society became the "umbrella" precinct of the other eleven precincts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fremantle.wa.gov.au/cityoffremantle/Community_engagement/Precincts |title=Precincts |author=City of Fremantle |accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref> It has remained such, and is the only one not defined by geographical boundaries (the others are mostly representative of a suburb).<ref>{{citation |title=Precinct Map |author=City of Fremantle |url=http://www.fremantle.wa.gov.au/files/61955BCB-171E-4DD2-8DA1-9F9E00AF7389/precinct_map.pdf |accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref> The work of precinct groups can be supported by financial assistance from the City of up to $850 per year (as long as this is not used to support government election campaigning).<ref>{{citation |title=Precinct Guidelines |author=City of Fremantle |date=August 2012 |url=http://www.fremantle.wa.gov.au/files/61955BCB-171E-4DD2-8DA1-9F9E00AF7389/precinct_map.pdf |accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref>
The overall nature of the Society's work is ongoing due to the inherent pressures from developers and others.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Dawkins, Jeremy | author2=MacGill, Gerry | title=The politics of planning in Fremantle | journal=Urban Policy and Research | publication-date=June 1990 | volume=8 | issue=2 | pages=81–85 | issn=0811-1146 | doi=10.1080/08111149008551432| year=1990 }}</ref>
''Fighting for Fremantle'', a history of the Society by Ron and Dianne Davidson, was published by [[Fremantle Press]] in 2010. It was launched by the Premier of [[Western Australia]], [[Colin Barnett]], in [[Victoria Hall (Fremantle)|Victoria Hall]].
== Campaigns == The Society has led campaigns to prevent the loss of many significant buildings in Fremantle; not all have been successful. Some examples include: * The [[Oriana Cinema]], an [[art deco]] building on the corner of High and Queen Streets (demolished in 1972). * [[Fremantle Markets]]. * The proposed widening of High Street and demolition of all buildings along the south side of the road. * [[Fremantle Prison]]. * [[Victoria Quay, Fremantle|Victoria Quay]] development, which in 2014 is still under discussion.{{update after|2015|01|01}}
Other projects have also been undertaken, such as the 1978–80 photographic survey of almost every building in Fremantle, and the [[Freopedia]] wikitown project.{{update after|2015|01|01}}
